<article>
    <h1>Work&#xAD;horse chairs</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201031/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-31"><time>2020-10-31</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE DESIGN</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Luke Lim (left), 40, de­sign prin­ci­pal, Llark Ar­chi­tects</p>
    <p>The Span Lounge Chair (right) by Hen­rik Ped­er­sen checks all the boxes for me as a trusty of­fice work­mate.</p>
    <p>I like the “keep-it-sim­ple” phi­los­o­phy for of­fice chairs so the fewer mov­ing parts in my seat, the bet­ter.</p>
    <p>With typ­i­cal of­fice chairs, I tend to lean back and of­ten suf­fer the sud­den shock of the seat re­clin­ing back too fast.</p>
    <p>Also, chairs with many parts, nooks and cran­nies take longer to wipe down and may col­lect dirt and dust more eas­ily.</p>
    <p>Er­gonomics is a key con­sid­er­a­tion, as I am usu­ally sit­ting for more than 10 hours a day, work­ing on de­sign and ar­chi­tec­tural drafts.</p>
    <p>Given how most of the firm’s meet­ings are now in front of the com­puter screen, I tend to be seated for even longer pe­ri­ods some­times.</p>
    <p>I be­lieve ro­bust­ness and ease of main­te­nance are also con­cerns that have be­come more prom­i­nent re­cently.</p>
    <p>In terms of ma­te­ri­als, I think an elas­tic mesh af­fords good com­fort. How­ever, in terms of the over­all con­struc­tion of a chair, I pre­fer to go with a tim­ber chair, like the Span, be­cause of its nat­u­ral feel.</p>

